<paper id="1981234161"><title>Matching is as easy as matrix inversion</title><year>1987</year><authors><author org="&quot;University of California, Berkeley&quot;" id="2695659904">Ketan Mulmuley</author><author org="Harvard University" id="391723092">Umesh V. Vazirani</author><author org="Cornell University, Ithaca -- NY" id="2012704994">Vijay V. Vazirani</author></authors><n_citation>108</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1510646708</reference><reference>1553674362</reference><reference>1655990431</reference><reference>1977568210</reference><reference>1980364701</reference><reference>1982800484</reference><reference>2006912660</reference><reference>2017205387</reference><reference>2046097442</reference><reference>2051283034</reference><reference>2056352038</reference><reference>2057512592</reference><reference>2062881752</reference><reference>2079828065</reference><reference>2080132708</reference><reference>2085750496</reference><reference>2113097540</reference><reference>2610729871</reference></references><venue id="1190910084" type="C">Symposium on the Theory of Computing</venue><doi>10.1145/28395.383347</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.46759">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Graph</keyword><keyword weight="0.46166">Combinatorics</keyword><keyword weight="0.54302">Matrix (mathematics)</keyword><keyword weight="0.4294">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.43041">Inversion (meteorology)</keyword><keyword weight="0.60564">Matching (graph theory)</keyword><keyword weight="0.50024">Probabilistic logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.61885">Integer matrix</keyword><keyword weight="0.66127">Lemma (mathematics)</keyword></keywords><publisher>ACM</publisher><abstract>We present a new algorithm for finding a maximum matching in a general graph. The special feature of our algorithm is that its only computationally non-trivial step is the inversion of a single integer matrix. Since this step can be parallelized, we get a simple parallel (RNC 2) algorithm. At the heart of our algorithm lies a probabilistic lemma, the isolating lemma. We show other applications of this lemma to parallel computation and randomized reductions.</abstract></paper>